content:
Special Cases for Matching Records with the augment Transformation

Handling Null Keys

When a record in the left dataset contains a null key, CRM Analytics appends the right columns and inserts null for dimensions, including dates, and '0' for measures.

Example: Applying the augment transformation on datasets with a relationship to "Price," and matching records based on the Id and ProdId fields. The last record is not matched because its product ID is null.

Handling Empty Keys

CRM Analytics matches empty-value left keys and empty-value right keys.

Example: Applying the augment transformation on datasets with a relationship to "Price," and matching records based on the Id and ProdId fields. The last record in the Product dataset matches the third record in the Price dataset because both have empty values ("").

Handling Non-Unique Keys

Although it's recommended, the left key doesn't have to be unique. If multiple records have the same left key, CRM Analytics creates the same values for the appended columns.

Example: Applying the augment transformation on datasets with a relationship to "Price," and matching records based on the Id and ProdId fields. Multiple records in the Product dataset match records in the Price dataset.

Handling No Match

If the left key doesn't have a match in the right data stream, CRM Analytics appends the right columns, inserting nulls for dimensions, including dates, and sets measures based on whether null measure handling is enabled.

Example: Applying the augment transformation on datasets with a relationship to "Price," and matching records based on the Id and ProdId fields. No keys match, resulting in no matched records.

Handling Multiple Matches

If the left dataset has a one-to-many relationship with the right dataset, CRM Analytics can find multiple matches for a left record. The specified augment operation determines what CRM Analytics does with multiple matches.

LookupSingleValue: The augment transformation returns results from a single row. CRM Analytics randomly selects one row from the list of matched rows.

Example: Applying the augment transformation on datasets with a relationship to "Price," setting the operation to LookupSingleValue, and matching records based on the Id and ProdId fields. Although there are multiple rows for Prod3 in the Price dataset, CRM Analytics randomly chooses one matching row.

LookupMultiValue: CRM Analytics returns results from all matched rows.

Example: Applying the augment transformation on datasets with a relationship to "Price," setting the operation to LookupMultiValue, and matching records based on the Id and ProdId fields. The dimension Price.Pricebook field in the resulting dataset becomes a multivalue field, showing all dimension values.
title: Handling Special Cases with CRM Analytics Augment Transformation
